  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2695887992" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2695887992" />
    <a title="Chip Hunter" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19578583-chip-hunter"><img alt="Chip Hunter" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1548879669p2/19578583.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2695887992?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chip Hunter" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chip Hunter" href="/user/show/19578583-chip-hunter">Chip Hunter</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2695887992" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16217419732341864075">While preparing to write my review I was surprised to see a lot of harsh criticism for this book. I thought it showed great improvement over the first in the Merlin Cycle. While I still find Merlin a little too much like Corwin (but not as likeable), I am getting used to him and don’t find myself as irritated as I did in the first book. The plot in BLOOD OF AMBER picks up the pace, with Merlin aggressively pursuing his would-be murderer and finding himself embroiled in a multi-realm-spanning plo</span>
  <span id="freeText16217419732341864075" style="display:none">While preparing to write my review I was surprised to see a lot of harsh criticism for this book. I thought it showed great improvement over the first in the Merlin Cycle. While I still find Merlin a little too much like Corwin (but not as likeable), I am getting used to him and don’t find myself as irritated as I did in the first book. The plot in BLOOD OF AMBER picks up the pace, with Merlin aggressively pursuing his would-be murderer and finding himself embroiled in a multi-realm-spanning plot to take down Amber. Some of the criticism I saw focused on the unlimited seeming powers of Merlin, who having inherited the powers of both Amber and Chaos must be the most powerful person alive. While valid, I still think Delany did a fine job of making Merlin vulnerable, usually due to his own lack of caution and failure of forethought. I thought the revelations surrounding the still-mysterious body changer, Luke Raynard, and Dara were all important pieces to the overarching story and helped keep me engrossed in this book, though there remains a great deal to uncover regarding who is really pulling the strings here. Another thing I enjoyed about BLOOD OF AMBER was finally getting a glimpse of what the Courts of Chaos are like. During Merlin’s reminisces about his psychotic half-brother’s repeated attempts to murder him (seems like a good candidate for being the one behind the more recent attempts…) we glimpse a world governed by unfamiliar physics where violence seems common. Hopefully more revelations regarding life in the Courts is coming. The strangest and most incongruous thing about the series thus far is the inclusion of Ghostwheel. It has played almost no important part, simply serving as a strange and unexplained distraction. I’m sure it must be important for later parts of the story, but it has been sloppily handled to this point. Still, I am encouraged by the second volume in the Merlin Cycle and look forward to continuing the story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16217419732341864075" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

